       "          const element = document.querySelector('#df-afec75fc-9ba2-423b-b1fc-19853863ec24');\n",
       "          const dataTable =\n",
       "            await google.colab.kernel.invokeFunction('convertToInteractive',\n",
       "                                                     [key], {});\n",
       "          if (!dataTable) return;\n",
       "\n",
       "          const docLinkHtml = 'Like what you see? Visit the ' +\n",
       "            '<a target=\"_blank\" href=https://colab.research.google.com/notebooks/data_table.ipynb>data table notebook</a>'\n",
       "            + ' to learn more about interactive tables.';\n",
       "          element.innerHTML = '';\n",
       "          dataTable['output_type'] = 'display_data';\n",
       "          await google.colab.output.renderOutput(dataTable, element);\n",
       "          const docLink = document.createElement('div');\n",
       "          docLink.innerHTML = docLinkHtml;\n",
       "          element.appendChild(docLink);\n",
       "        }\n",
       "      </script>\n",

   "source": [
    "# filling missing values of continous values using mean\n",
    "print('before fill: ', df['CREDIT'].isnull().sum())\n",
    "df['CREDIT'].fillna(df['CREDIT'].mean(),inplace=True)\n",
    "df['INCOME_TOTAL'].fillna(df['INCOME_TOTAL'].mean(),inplace=True)\n",
    "df.fillna\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "aprioridf['CREDIT'].fillna(aprioridf['CREDIT'].mean(),inplace=True)\n",
    "aprioridf['INCOME_TOTAL'].fillna(aprioridf['INCOME_TOTAL'].mean(),inplace=True)\n",
    "aprioridf.fillna\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "print('after fill: ', df['CREDIT'].isnull().sum())"
   ]

   "source": [
    "# filling missing values of categorical & discrete values using mode\n",
    "print('missing values before: ', df.isnull().sum().sum())\n",
    "df['CODE_GENDER'].fillna(value=df['CODE_GENDER'].mode()[0], inplace=True)\n",
    "df['OCCUPATION_TYPE'].fillna(value=df['OCCUPATION_TYPE'].mode()[0], inplace=True)\n",
    "df['FAM_MEMBERS'].fillna(value=df['FAM_MEMBERS'].mode()[0], inplace=True)\n",
    "\n",
    "aprioridf['CODE_GENDER'].fillna(value=aprioridf['CODE_GENDER'].mode()[0], inplace=True)\n",
    "aprioridf['OCCUPATION_TYPE'].fillna(value=aprioridf['OCCUPATION_TYPE'].mode()[0], inplace=True)\n",

   "source": [
    "# Values of 'INCOME_TOTAL\" and \"CREDIT\" were only normalized because they were the only continous data type columns\n",
    "\n",
    "mean_income = df['INCOME_TOTAL'].mean()\n",
    "std_income = df['INCOME_TOTAL'].std()\n",
    "mean_credit = df['CREDIT'].mean()\n",
    "std_credit = df['CREDIT'].std()\n",
    "\n",
    "df['INCOME_TOTAL'] = df['INCOME_TOTAL'] - mean_income\n",
    "df['INCOME_TOTAL'] = df['INCOME_TOTAL'] / std_income\n",
    "\n",
    "df['CREDIT'] = df['CREDIT'] - mean_credit\n",
    "df['CREDIT'] =  df['CREDIT'] / std_credit\n",
    "\n",
    "df"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 18,
   "metadata": {
    "colab": {
     "base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/",
     "height": 783
    },
    "id": "IZ3zLWv79r_C",
    "outputId": "055c08dd-df3a-4ffe-9bd9-fc91ea2b02fd"
   },

       "        buttonEl.style.display =\n",
       "          google.colab.kernel.accessAllowed ? 'block' : 'none';\n",
       "\n",
       "        async function convertToInteractive(key) {\n",
       "          const element = document.querySelector('#df-c1f2b644-1284-49be-bad8-50a0c76a357d');\n",
       "          const dataTable =\n",
       "            await google.colab.kernel.invokeFunction('convertToInteractive',\n",
       "                                                     [key], {});\n",
       "          if (!dataTable) return;\n",
       "\n",
       "          const docLinkHtml = 'Like what you see? Visit the ' +\n",
       "            '<a target=\"_blank\" href=https://colab.research.google.com/notebooks/data_table.ipynb>data table notebook</a>'\n",
       "            + ' to learn more about interactive tables.';\n",
       "          element.innerHTML = '';\n",
       "          dataTable['output_type'] = 'display_data';\n",
       "          await google.colab.output.renderOutput(dataTable, element);\n",
       "          const docLink = document.createElement('div');\n",
       "          docLink.innerHTML = docLinkHtml;\n",
       "          element.appendChild(docLink);\n",
       "        }\n",
       "      </script>\n",
       "    </div>\n",
       "  </div>\n",
       "  "
      ],

    "X = df['NAME_CONTRACT_TYPE'].unique()\n",
    "\n",
    "X_axis = np.arange(len(X))\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.figure(figsize=(15,10))\n",
    "plt.bar(X_axis - 0.2, y1, 0.4, label = 'Defaulters')\n",
    "# addlabels(X, y1)\n",
    "plt.bar(X_axis + 0.2, y2, 0.4, label = 'Non-defaulters')\n",
    "# addlabels(X, y2)\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.xticks(X_axis, X)\n",
    "plt.xlabel(\"Contract Types\")\n",
    "plt.ylabel(\"Count\")\n",
    "plt.title(\"Number of defaulters & non-Defaulters for different contracts\")\n",
    "plt.legend()\n",
    "for i, w, m in zip(X_axis, y1, y2):\n",
    "    plt.text(i, w + 10, str(w), color='b', \n",
    "             horizontalalignment='right')\n",
    "\n",
    "    plt.text(i + 0.25, m + 10, str(m), color='r', \n",
    "             horizontalalignment='right')\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]

       "        async function convertToInteractive(key) {\n",
       "          const element = document.querySelector('#df-03db244e-7c78-423a-b9e9-e84b1bcf1848');\n",
       "          const dataTable =\n",
       "            await google.colab.kernel.invokeFunction('convertToInteractive',\n",
       "                                                     [key], {});\n",
       "          if (!dataTable) return;\n",
       "\n",
       "          const docLinkHtml = 'Like what you see? Visit the ' +\n",
       "            '<a target=\"_blank\" href=https://colab.research.google.com/notebooks/data_table.ipynb>data table notebook</a>'\n",
       "            + ' to learn more about interactive tables.';\n",
       "          element.innerHTML = '';\n",
       "          dataTable['output_type'] = 'display_data';\n",
       "          await google.colab.output.renderOutput(dataTable, element);\n",
       "          const docLink = document.createElement('div');\n",
       "          docLink.innerHTML = docLinkHtml;\n",
       "          element.appendChild(docLink);\n",
       "        }\n",
       "      </script>\n",
       "    </div>\n",
       "  </div>\n",

    "columns = ['NAME_CONTRACT_TYPE','CODE_GENDER','FLAG_OWN_CAR','FLAG_OWN_REALTY','NAME_INCOME_TYPE','EDUCATION_TYPE','FAMILY_STATUS','HOUSING_TYPE','OCCUPATION_TYPE','ORGANIZATION_TYPE']\n",

       "        async function convertToInteractive(key) {\n",
       "          const element = document.querySelector('#df-bdb439a4-62c2-4754-9cc1-87217d7d5f79');\n",
       "          const dataTable =\n",
       "            await google.colab.kernel.invokeFunction('convertToInteractive',\n",
       "                                                     [key], {});\n",
       "          if (!dataTable) return;\n",
       "\n",
       "          const docLinkHtml = 'Like what you see? Visit the ' +\n",
       "            '<a target=\"_blank\" href=https://colab.research.google.com/notebooks/data_table.ipynb>data table notebook</a>'\n",
       "            + ' to learn more about interactive tables.';\n",
       "          element.innerHTML = '';\n",
       "          dataTable['output_type'] = 'display_data';\n",
       "          await google.colab.output.renderOutput(dataTable, element);\n",
       "          const docLink = document.createElement('div');\n",
       "          docLink.innerHTML = docLinkHtml;\n",
       "          element.appendChild(docLink);\n",
       "        }\n",
       "      </script>\n",

    "contigency_table = pd.crosstab(final_df['TARGET'],\n",
    "                            final_df['REGION_RATING_CLIENT'])\n",
    "print(contigency_table)\n",
    "contigency_table1 = pd.crosstab(final_df['TARGET'],\n",
    "                            final_df['FAM_MEMBERS'])\n",
    "print(contigency_table1)\n",
    "contigency_table2 = pd.crosstab(final_df['TARGET'],\n",
    "                            final_df['CNT_CHILDREN'])\n",
    "print(contigency_table2)\n",
    "contigency_table3 = pd.crosstab(final_df['TARGET'],\n",
    "                            final_df['OCCUPATION_TYPE'])\n",
    "print(contigency_table3)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "id": "G-4X_FIxlJF3"
   },
   "source": [
    "**Comments:**\n",
    "\n",
    "The above contingency table shows the different frequencies between the variable Target and others, region rating, family members, number of children and occupation type. The contigency table is further used to carry out a chi square test to test our hypothesis whehter there is a significant relaitonship between above variables."
   ]
  },

    "chi_sqr = stats.chi2_contingency(contigency_table)\n",

   "source": [
    "**Comments:**\n",
    "\n",
    "The chi square test is conducted to determine whether there is a significant relationship between the above variables. A large chi square value would impy there is a significant relationship between the two variables. For the above results since the chi square value is pretty large and the value of p is greater than the assumed significant value we can assume there is a significant relationship between Target and region rating, target and family members, target and number of childre, target and the type of occupation. The attribute target(defaulter or non defaulter depends on the region rating of client, number of family members, number of children and type of occupation.*italicized text*"
   ]

       "            await google.colab.kernel.invokeFunction('convertToInteractive',\n",
       "                                                     [key], {});\n",
       "          if (!dataTable) return;\n",
       "\n",
       "          const docLinkHtml = 'Like what you see? Visit the ' +\n",
       "            '<a target=\"_blank\" href=https://colab.research.google.com/notebooks/data_table.ipynb>data table notebook</a>'\n",
       "            + ' to learn more about interactive tables.';\n",
       "          element.innerHTML = '';\n",
       "          dataTable['output_type'] = 'display_data';\n",
       "          await google.colab.output.renderOutput(dataTable, element);\n",
       "          const docLink = document.createElement('div');\n",
       "          docLink.innerHTML = docLinkHtml;\n",
       "          element.appendChild(docLink);\n",
       "        }\n",

    "highest_allowed = mydf['INCOME_TOTAL'].mean() + 3*mydf['INCOME_TOTAL'].std()\n",
    "lowest_allowed = mydf['INCOME_TOTAL'].mean() - 3*mydf['INCOME_TOTAL'].std()\n",
    "print(\"Highest allowed\", highest_allowed)\n",
    "print(\"Lowest allowed\", lowest_allowed)"

       "            '<a target=\"_blank\" href=https://colab.research.google.com/notebooks/data_table.ipynb>data table notebook</a>'\n",

       "        }\n",

    "new_df = mydf[(mydf['INCOME_TOTAL'] < highest_allowed) & (mydf['INCOME_TOTAL'] > lowest_allowed)]\n",

   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "id": "VsGTrufo3uSg"
   },
   "source": [
    "**Comments:** Now in new_df all the outliers in INCOME_TOTAL are removed. This is one approach. But we will use capping approach. In capping, instead of removing outliers we convert them and bring them in range of our data. Because they may contain useful information. \n",
    "The capping is used below"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "id": "EfVSN8uK4QC6"
   },
   "source": [
    "**Capping INCOME_TOTAL outliers:**"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 47,
   "metadata": {
    "id": "V7tZiQzYwA9u"
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "upper_limit = mydf['INCOME_TOTAL'].mean() + 3*mydf['INCOME_TOTAL'].std()\n",
    "lower_limit = mydf['INCOME_TOTAL'].mean() - 3*mydf['INCOME_TOTAL'].std()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 48,
   "metadata": {
    "id": "dBL_AtCcwRNF"
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "mydf['INCOME_TOTAL'] = np.where(\n",
    "    mydf['INCOME_TOTAL']>upper_limit,\n",
    "    upper_limit,\n",
    "    np.where(\n",
    "        mydf['INCOME_TOTAL']<lower_limit,\n",
    "        lower_limit,\n",
    "        mydf['INCOME_TOTAL']\n",
    "    )\n",
    ")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "id": "1uyHjHn34WPp"

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "id": "tcQ6HfvR6eN3"
   },
   "source": [
    "**Capping outliers in REGION_RATING_CLIENT**"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 57,
   "metadata": {
    "id": "5hgxtktu5zrh"
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "upper_limit = mydf['REGION_RATING_CLIENT'].mean() + 3*mydf['REGION_RATING_CLIENT'].std()\n",
    "lower_limit = mydf['REGION_RATING_CLIENT'].mean() - 3*mydf['REGION_RATING_CLIENT'].std()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 58,
   "metadata": {
    "id": "AzCZWV4W5ztT"
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "mydf['REGION_RATING_CLIENT'] = np.where(\n",
    "    mydf['REGION_RATING_CLIENT']>upper_limit,\n",
    "    upper_limit,\n",
    "    np.where(\n",
    "        mydf['REGION_RATING_CLIENT']<lower_limit,\n",
    "        lower_limit,\n",
    "        mydf['REGION_RATING_CLIENT']\n",
    "    )\n",
    ")"
   ]
  },

    "### For frequent pattern mining, apriori algorithm is used. The algorithm is mainly used for market based analysis to find out associations between different items and products. Apriori algorithm uses frequent itemsets to generate association rules which can then be filtered out for better analysis of the results."

       "          const dataTable =\n",
       "            await google.colab.kernel.invokeFunction('convertToInteractive',\n",
       "                                                     [key], {});\n",
       "          if (!dataTable) return;\n",
       "\n",
       "          const docLinkHtml = 'Like what you see? Visit the ' +\n",
       "            '<a target=\"_blank\" href=https://colab.research.google.com/notebooks/data_table.ipynb>data table notebook</a>'\n",
       "            + ' to learn more about interactive tables.';\n",
       "          element.innerHTML = '';\n",
       "          dataTable['output_type'] = 'display_data';\n",
       "          await google.colab.output.renderOutput(dataTable, element);\n",
       "          const docLink = document.createElement('div');\n",
       "          docLink.innerHTML = docLinkHtml;\n",
       "          element.appendChild(docLink);\n",
       "        }\n",
       "      </script>\n",

   "source": [
    "####Some of the data in our dataset is not categorical. The columns of total income and credit has large amount of continuous data. Since our algorithm only accepts categorical data, the continous data was discretized, split into bins and labaled. For this the pandas qcut was used. qcut splits data into equal sized bins and the bins are defined using percentiles based on the data. The dsicretized data is added as a new column to the dataframe.\n",
    "\n"
   ]
  },

       "          const dataTable =\n",
       "            await google.colab.kernel.invokeFunction('convertToInteractive',\n",
       "                                                     [key], {});\n",
       "          if (!dataTable) return;\n",
       "\n",
       "          const docLinkHtml = 'Like what you see? Visit the ' +\n",
       "            '<a target=\"_blank\" href=https://colab.research.google.com/notebooks/data_table.ipynb>data table notebook</a>'\n",
       "            + ' to learn more about interactive tables.';\n",
       "          element.innerHTML = '';\n",
       "          dataTable['output_type'] = 'display_data';\n",
       "          await google.colab.output.renderOutput(dataTable, element);\n",
       "          const docLink = document.createElement('div');\n",
       "          docLink.innerHTML = docLinkHtml;\n",

       "        }\n",

    "#nmaking bins for continuous data\n",
    "#for count children\n",
    "print(aprioridf['CNT_CHILDREN'].describe())\n",
    "aprioridf['CNT_CHILDREN_RANGE'] = pd.qcut(aprioridf['CNT_CHILDREN'], q=4, labels=['<=1', '>1'], duplicates = 'drop')\n",
    "print(aprioridf['CNT_CHILDREN_RANGE'].value_counts())\n",
    "\n",
    "#for income total\n",
    "print(aprioridf['INCOME_TOTAL'].describe())\n",
    "aprioridf['INCOME_TOTAL_RANGE'] = pd.qcut(aprioridf['INCOME_TOTAL'], q=4, labels=['25,649 < Income <=112,500', '112,500 < Income <= 157,500', '202,500 < Income <=117,000,000', '157,500 < Income <=202,500' ],duplicates = 'drop')\n",
    "print(aprioridf['INCOME_TOTAL_RANGE'].value_counts())\n",
    "\n",
    "#for credit\n",
    "print(aprioridf['CREDIT'].describe())\n",
    "aprioridf['CREDIT_RANGE'] = pd.qcut(aprioridf['CREDIT'], q=4 , labels=['270,000 < Credit <=518,562', '45,000 < Credit <=270,000', '518,562 < Credit <=810,000', '810,000 < Credit <=4,050,000' ], duplicates = 'drop')\n",
    "print(aprioridf['CREDIT_RANGE'].value_counts())\n",
    "\n",
    "#for family members\n",
    "print(aprioridf['FAM_MEMBERS'].describe())\n",
    "aprioridf['FAM_MEMBERS_RANGE'] = pd.qcut(aprioridf['FAM_MEMBERS'] , q = 4 ,labels=['<=2', '>2 <=3', '>3 <=20'], duplicates = 'drop')\n",
    "print(aprioridf['FAM_MEMBERS_RANGE'].value_counts())\n",
    "\n",
    "aprioridf.head(15)"
   ]

    "id": "OWTkXDavj16V"

   "source": [
    "#### The apriori algorithm only accepts boolean values. Hence all the categorical data in the dataframe is converted to new columns for each category. For example the columns TARGET, a new column for target value 0 and another for target value 1 would be made. This is done for all of our data. This way our data would have a column for each category of a columns. The data is now in the form of boolean value and is ready for our algorithm. "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "id": "L99UnxhMAOYe"
   },
   "source": [
    "### The following table shows how the numerical data was discretized. There were four categories made for the credit column. The data was divided almost equally among these four categories. The total income was also divided into four categories. The number of children was divided into two categories less than 1 and then greater than 1 and less than 19. The categories were made since a large number of entries had a count of 1 for children and very few had greater than 1 and less than 19. The division for number of family members was also done in the same way. "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "id": "AU8mvKkF-uHX"
   },
   "source": [
    "| Credit Category | Total Income Category | Number of Children | Number of Family Members |\n",
    "| --- | --- | --- | ---|\n",
    "| 270,000 < Credit <=518,562 | 25,649 < Income <=112,500 | 0 < Number <=1 | Number <= 2 |\n",
    "| 45,000 < Credit <=270,000  | 112,500 < Income <= 157,500| 1 < Number <= 19 | 2 < Number <= 3|\n",
    "| 518,562 < Credit <=810,000  | 202,500 < Income <=117,000,000| | 3 < Number <=20 |\n",
    "| 810,000 < Credit <=4,050,000| 157,500 < Income <=202,500|"

   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "id": "sBHBXbHzmYvg"
   },
   "source": [
    "## APRIORI ALGORITHM"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "id": "gVsOkwPYkCXQ"
   },
   "source": [
    "The algorithm makes use of support, confidence and list. Support is the relative frequency that the rules show up. Confidence is the probability of B happening given that A happened. It is is a measure of the reliability of the rule. The confidence value in the table shows how likely is the entry in the consequent column is expected to occur given that the entry in the column antecedents is present. Lift is the ratio of the observed support to that expected if the two rules were independent. A lift value of greater than 1 shows that the entries are likely to occur together."
   ]
  },
  {

       "      <script>\n",
       "        const buttonEl =\n",
       "          document.querySelector('#df-a1a89bcd-0a2d-468d-b3fb-95a42ada1eab button.colab-df-convert');\n",
       "        buttonEl.style.display =\n",
       "          google.colab.kernel.accessAllowed ? 'block' : 'none';\n",
       "\n",
       "        async function convertToInteractive(key) {\n",
       "          const element = document.querySelector('#df-a1a89bcd-0a2d-468d-b3fb-95a42ada1eab');\n",
       "          const dataTable =\n",
       "            await google.colab.kernel.invokeFunction('convertToInteractive',\n",
       "                                                     [key], {});\n",
       "          if (!dataTable) return;\n",
       "\n",
       "          const docLinkHtml = 'Like what you see? Visit the ' +\n",
       "            '<a target=\"_blank\" href=https://colab.research.google.com/notebooks/data_table.ipynb>data table notebook</a>'\n",
       "            + ' to learn more about interactive tables.';\n",
       "          element.innerHTML = '';\n",
       "          dataTable['output_type'] = 'display_data';\n",
       "          await google.colab.output.renderOutput(dataTable, element);\n",
       "          const docLink = document.createElement('div');\n",
       "          docLink.innerHTML = docLinkHtml;\n",
       "          element.appendChild(docLink);\n",
       "        }\n",
       "      </script>\n",
       "    </div>\n",
       "  </div>\n",
       "  "
      ],

     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "#apriori implementaion\n",
    "#Apriori min support\n",
    "min_support = 0.2\n",
    "#Max lenght of apriori n-grams\n",
    "max_len = 15\n",
    "frequent_items = apriori(aprioridf, use_colnames=True, min_support=min_support, max_len=max_len + 1)\n",
    "rules = association_rules(frequent_items, metric='lift', min_threshold=1)\n",
    "# rules\n",
    "rules.head(50).sort_values(by='confidence', ascending=False)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "id": "XcnQ4OoIkKHE"
   },
   "source": [
    "#### comments on results:\n",
    " For the abve results, minimum confidence is set as 0.2 since the dataset is huge. The resulting rules are sorted according to the confidence in descending order. The first row shows us that there is a significant relationship between a customer having cash loans and them having a credit greater than 810,000 and less than 4,050,000. This can be verified from a high confidence value of 0.98. This shows that out of all the data containing credit in the mentioned range, 98 percent of data also contains contract type of cash loans. \n",
    "Interpreting the third rule which is between higher education and target 0. The rule has a confidence value of 0.946. This shows that the customers having education type of higher education, 95 percent have target value of 0, i.e they are a defaulter. \n",
    " \n",
    "Other rules with high confidence, indicate that if a customer has higher education, credit less than 270,000 , is a female, owns car, is married, is a commerical associate, then it is more likely that the customer is a defaulter. Similar frequent relationships can also be drawn from other rules. "
   ]
  },

       "        async function convertToInteractive(key) {\n",
       "          const element = document.querySelector('#df-5ef78ee6-6407-41d6-beba-45874911dc76');\n",
       "          const dataTable =\n",
       "            await google.colab.kernel.invokeFunction('convertToInteractive',\n",
       "                                                     [key], {});\n",
       "          if (!dataTable) return;\n",
       "\n",
       "          const docLinkHtml = 'Like what you see? Visit the ' +\n",
       "            '<a target=\"_blank\" href=https://colab.research.google.com/notebooks/data_table.ipynb>data table notebook</a>'\n",
       "            + ' to learn more about interactive tables.';\n",
       "          element.innerHTML = '';\n",
       "          dataTable['output_type'] = 'display_data';\n",
       "          await google.colab.output.renderOutput(dataTable, element);\n",
       "          const docLink = document.createElement('div');\n",
       "          docLink.innerHTML = docLinkHtml;\n",
       "          element.appendChild(docLink);\n",
       "        }\n",
       "      </script>\n",
       "    </div>\n",
       "  </div>\n",

   "source": [
    "#Apriori min support\n",
    "min_support = 0.2\n",
    "#Max lenght of apriori n-grams\n",
    "max_len = 3\n",
    "frequent_items = apriori(aprioridf, use_colnames=True, min_support=min_support, max_len=max_len + 1)\n",
    "rules = association_rules(frequent_items, metric='lift', min_threshold=1)\n",
    "target = '{\\'TARGET_0\\'}'\n",
    "results_attrition_no = rules[rules['consequents'].astype(str).str.contains(target, na=False)].sort_values(by='confidence', ascending=False)\n",
    "results_attrition_no.head(10)"
   ]

       "        async function convertToInteractive(key) {\n",
       "          const element = document.querySelector('#df-fd92c4d7-9659-41f7-9e61-ad9d5e99fd68');\n",
       "          const dataTable =\n",
       "            await google.colab.kernel.invokeFunction('convertToInteractive',\n",
       "                                                     [key], {});\n",
       "          if (!dataTable) return;\n",
       "\n",
       "          const docLinkHtml = 'Like what you see? Visit the ' +\n",
       "            '<a target=\"_blank\" href=https://colab.research.google.com/notebooks/data_table.ipynb>data table notebook</a>'\n",
       "            + ' to learn more about interactive tables.';\n",
       "          element.innerHTML = '';\n",
       "          dataTable['output_type'] = 'display_data';\n",
       "          await google.colab.output.renderOutput(dataTable, element);\n",
       "          const docLink = document.createElement('div');\n",
       "          docLink.innerHTML = docLinkHtml;\n",
       "          element.appendChild(docLink);\n",
       "        }\n",
       "      </script>\n",

   "source": [
    "#apriori implementaion\n",
    "#Apriori min support\n",
    "min_support = 0.2\n",
    "#Max lenght of apriori n-grams\n",
    "max_len = 15\n",
    "frequent_items = apriori(aprioridf, use_colnames=True, min_support=min_support, max_len=max_len + 1)\n",
    "rules = association_rules(frequent_items, metric='lift', min_threshold=1)\n",
    "# rules\n",
    "rules.head(50).sort_values(by='support', ascending=False)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "id": "9jmyMB1eG749"
   },
   "source": [
    "### Instead of sorting the rules by confidence, we have sorted them by their support value for comparison. Rule one has a high support value for Target Value 0 and count of children <= 1. The rule has a relatively high confidence value and a lift of greater than 1. This shows that target value 0 occurs most frequently with count children <= 1. The high confidence shows that 90 percent people of who are defaulter are likely to have children less than or equal to one. \n",
    "##Sorting the data accroding to support is similar to sorting it according to confidence. Support, confidence and lift, all three are properties of the data and tell us different things about the association between the attributes, however all three of them should be analysed to determine which relationships are the most meaningful."
   ]
  },

    "from sklearn.preprocessing import LabelEncoder\n",
    "gle = LabelEncoder()\n",
    "columns = ['NAME_CONTRACT_TYPE','CODE_GENDER','FLAG_OWN_CAR','FLAG_OWN_REALTY','NAME_INCOME_TYPE','EDUCATION_TYPE','FAMILY_STATUS','HOUSING_TYPE','OCCUPATION_TYPE','ORGANIZATION_TYPE']\n",

   "source": [
    "distortions = []\n",
    "inertias = []\n",
    "mapping1 = {}\n",
    "mapping2 = {}\n",
    "K = range(1, 10)\n",
    " \n",
    "for k in K:\n",
    "    # Building and fitting the model\n",
    "    kmeanModel = KMeans(n_clusters=k).fit(X)\n",
    "    kmeanModel.fit(X)\n",
    " \n",
    "    distortions.append(sum(np.min(cdist(X, kmeanModel.cluster_centers_,\n",
    "                                        'euclidean'), axis=1)) / X.shape[0])\n",
    "    inertias.append(kmeanModel.inertia_)\n",
    " \n",
    "    mapping1[k] = sum(np.min(cdist(X, kmeanModel.cluster_centers_,\n",
    "                                   'euclidean'), axis=1)) / X.shape[0]\n",
    "    mapping2[k] = kmeanModel.inertia_\n",
    "    \n",
    "plt.plot(K, distortions, 'bx-')\n",
    "plt.xlabel('Values of K')\n",
    "plt.ylabel('Distortion')\n",
    "plt.title('The Elbow Method using Distortion')\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
